> Note: These solutions are different from other brute force with 4 for loops. I have tried to do it in single for loop without modifying the input marking visited. Follow the images to understand.

# Intuition

## Hint 1
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/b05a7500-de79-473f-9be4-4c5df6294f83_1683594102.628307.png)
It's all nice until a boundary comes and we need to change the direction of traversal. Can you track those boundaries for each direction?

## Hint 2
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/ce7e309f-7977-4bca-94f8-9b42ec6798bf_1683595355.2647583.png)
So, the initial boundaries are $[[0,n-1],[m-1,n-1],[m-1,0],[1,0]]$.
When we reach a boundary, change the direction of traversal by $90^o$ clockwise.

## Hint 3
Let $[r,c]$ be the current cell and the next cell is given as $[r',c'] = [r + dr, c + dc]$.
Here, $dr$ and $dc$ are the respective changes in row and column for different directions given as:
| Index | Direction | $dr$ | $dc$ |
| :-- | :-- | :--: | :--: |
| 0 | Right | 0 | 1 |
| 1 | Down | 1 | 0 |
| 2 | Left | 0 | -1 |
| 3 | Up | -1 | 0 |

Change in direction of traversal is $Right \rightarrow Down \rightarrow Left \rightarrow Up \rightarrow ...$

## Hint 4
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/6db646e6-7fcd-4672-9ebf-5ad24c1b8466_1683596857.2943535.png)
Suppose we have completed one spiral and standing at $8$. Now, we have the same problem but for a smaller matrix ($matrix[1...m-2][1...n-2]$). Recursion can be used.

---

***✔️ Solution - I (Recursion) [Accepted]***
Create a generalized version of the sub-matrix ($matrix[r_1 ... r_2][c_1 ... c_2]$) as 
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/37e13048-8064-4d7f-ab60-15f0ec113529_1683597332.3357146.png)
Boundaries will be $[[r_1,c_2],[r_2,c_2],[r_2,c_1],[r_1 + 1,c_1]]$.
Let $f(matrix[r_1 ... r_2][c_1 ... c_2])$ calculates for one spiral.
Recursively call on $f(matrix[r_1 + 1 ... r_2 - 1][c_1 + 1 ... c_2 - 1])$.

`total` is the area of one spiral, `total = area of outer rectangle - area of inner rectangle (if it exists)`.

**C++**
```
class Solution {
private:
    vector<int> result;

    void spiral(vector<vector<int>>& matrix, int r1, int r2, int c1, int c2) {
        int r12 = r2 - r1 + 1, c12 = c2 - c1 + 1;
        if (r12 <= 0 || c12 <= 0) {
            return;
        }
        int total = r12 * c12, dir = 0;
        if (r12 > 2 && c12 > 2) { // if inner rectangle exists
            total -= (r12 - 2) * (c12 - 2);
        }
        vector<int> curr = {r1, c1}; // curr = {r, c}
        vector<vector<int>> limit = {{r1, c2}, {r2, c2}, {r2, c1}, {r1 + 1, c1}}, // boundaries
        dCurr = {{0, 1}, {1, 0}, {0, -1}, {-1, 0}}; // dcurr = {dr, dc}
        for (int j = 0; j < total; j++) {
            result.push_back(matrix[curr[0]][curr[1]]);
            if (curr == limit[dir]) { // change direction
                dir = (dir + 1) % 4;
            }
            curr = {curr[0] + dCurr[dir][0], curr[1] + dCurr[dir][1]}; // next cell
        }
        spiral(matrix, r1 + 1, r2 - 1, c1 + 1, c2 - 1);
    }

public:
    vector<int> spiralOrder(vector<vector<int>>& matrix) {
        spiral(matrix, 0, matrix.size() - 1, 0, matrix[0].size() - 1);
        return result;
    }
};
```

---

***✔️ Solution - II (Iteration) [Accepted]***
Well, if you don't want to use recursion, everything was alright for one spiral above. But for next spiral, boundaries will change. Can we calculate how will they change?

Take the matrix from Hint 4
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/6db646e6-7fcd-4672-9ebf-5ad24c1b8466_1683596857.2943535.png)

The new sub-matrix and next spiral's boundaries will be
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/e054d689-e8fc-424a-8272-62876a53e5fa_1683605169.4419448.png)

Notice how the boundaries changed?
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/1a51b53c-f22b-4a83-b86e-810e927bd4dd_1683605580.8317032.png)

Boundaries change as

| Index | Direction | Boundary | Change | New Boundary |
| :-- | :-- | :-- | :-- | :-- |
| 0 | Right | $[0,n-1]$ | $[1,-1]$ | $[1,n-2]$ |
| 1 | Down | $[m-1,n-1]$ | $[-1,-1]$ | $[m-2,n-2]$ |
| 2 | Left | $[m-1,0]$ | $[-1,1]$ | $[m-2,1]$ |
| 3 | Up | $[1,0]$ | $[1,1]$ | $[2,1]$ |

Now these changes are constant. That is why it is a spiral.
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/63891d0f-cedd-44df-9366-04e1b9c7812c_1683607300.7183905.png)

Boundaries change by $[[1,-1], [-1,-1], [-1,1], [1,1]]$


**C++**
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> spiralOrder(vector<vector<int>>& matrix) {
        int m = matrix.size(), n = matrix[0].size(), dir = 0; // direction
        vector<int> result(m * n), curr = {0, 0}; // {r, c}
        vector<vector<int>> limit = {{0, n - 1}, {m - 1, n - 1}, {m - 1, 0}, {1, 0}}, // boundaries
        dCurr = {{0, 1}, {1, 0}, {0, -1}, {-1, 0}}, // {dr, dc}
        dLimit = {{1, -1}, {-1, -1}, {-1, 1}, {1, 1}}; // change in boundaries
        for (int i = 0; i < m * n; i++) {
            result[i] = matrix[curr[0]][curr[1]];
            if (curr == limit[dir]) { // change direction
                limit[dir] = {limit[dir][0] + dLimit[dir][0], limit[dir][1] + dLimit[dir][1]}; // change boundary
                dir = (dir + 1) % 4;
            }
            curr = {curr[0] + dCurr[dir][0], curr[1] + dCurr[dir][1]};
        }
        return result;
    }
};
```

---

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $O(mn)$
- Space complexity: $O(mn)$

