# Intuition
**step1)** go from  left-top corner to right most cell of  row 0.
**step2)** go from right-top corner to right-bottom cell of **column n-1**
 **step3)** go from right-bottom corner to left cell of column 0 .
**step4)** go left-bottom cell to up .
repeate it untill   **c1<=c2 and r1<=r2** where **c1=0,c2=matrix[0].size()-1;**
             __________________________________________and  **r1=0,r2=matrix.size()-1;**

# PLEASE upvote to motivate me more 
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> spiralOrder(vector<vector<int>>& matrix) {
        vector<int>ans;
        int c1=0,c2=matrix[0].size()-1;
        int r1=0,r2=matrix.size()-1;

        while(c1<=c2 && r1<=r2){
            for(int c=c1;c<=c2;++c){ //from left to right
                ans.push_back(matrix[r1][c]);
            }
            for(int r=r1+1;r<=r2;++r){ // from right top to bottom
                ans.push_back(matrix[r][c2]);
            }
            if(r1<r2 && c1<c2){
              for(int c=c2-1;c>=c1;--c){ //from bottom right to bottom left
                  ans.push_back(matrix[r2][c]);
              }
              for(int r=r2-1;r>r1;--r){ //from left bottom to left up
                  ans.push_back(matrix[r][c1]);
              }
            }

            r1++;
            r2--;
            c1++;
            c2--;

        }
        return ans;
    }
};


```
# Time Complexity :- O(m * n)
 where m is the number of rows and n is the number of columns in the matrix. This is because the code iterates over each element in the matrix exactly once in the worst case.

# Space Complexity :-O(m * n). 
This is because the code creates a vector of size m * n to store the output spiral order of the matrix.


