# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The problem asks for a list of integers representing a spiral order traversal of a given 2D matrix. My intuition for this code is to simulate the spiral traversal pattern by moving through the matrix in four directions: right, down, left, and up, while updating the boundaries of the submatrix. In conlusion I move from the outermost boundary towards the center until there are no more elements left to traverse.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
My approach for traversing a 2D matrix in a spiral order involves a systematic step-by-step process:

1. Initialization: Start with key variables:
start_row as 0 for the starting row.
end_row as n - 1 (n is the number of rows) for the ending row.
start_col at 0 for the starting column.
end_col as m - 1 (m is the number of columns) for the ending column.
Create an empty list called integerList to store spiral order elements.
2. Spiral Traversal Loop: Utilize a loop to visit all elements.

3. Traverse Top Row (left to right): In the loop, move along the top row left to right:
Use a for loop with j from start_col to end_col.
Add arr[start_row][j] to integerList.

4. Traverse Right Column (top to bottom): Proceed to the rightmost column from top to bottom:
      Use a for loop with i from start_row + 1 to end_row.
      Add arr[i][end_col] to integerList.

5. Traverse Bottom Row (right to left) if needed: If multiple rows are left (start_row < end_row), navigate the bottom row right to left:
Employ a for loop with j from end_col - 1 to start_col.
Append arr[end_row][j] to integerList.

6. Traverse Left Column (bottom to top) if needed: If multiple columns are left (start_col < end_col), travel the leftmost column from bottom to top:
Use a for loop with i from end_row - 1 to start_row + 1.
Add arr[i][start_col] to integerList.

7. Update Boundaries: After one spiral loop, adjust start_col, start_row (inward movement), and end_col, end_row (boundary reduction).

8. Repeat Steps 3-7: Continue these steps until all matrix elements are visited.
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
In terms of complexity, the time complexity is O(n * m) since each element is visited once, where 'n' is the number of rows and 'm' is the number of columns.
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The space complexity is also O(n * m) because 'integerList' stores all matrix elements in spiral order.
# Code
```
class Solution {
    public List<Integer> spiralOrder(int[][] arr) {
        List<Integer> integerList = new ArrayList<>();

        int n = arr.length;
        int m = arr[0].length;

        int start_row = 0;
        int end_row = n - 1;
        int start_col = 0;
        int end_col = m - 1;

        while (start_row <= end_row && start_col <= end_col) {
            // printing top elements
            for (int j = start_col; j <= end_col; j++) {
                integerList.add(arr[start_row][j]);
            }

            // printing right elements
            for (int i = start_row + 1; i <= end_row; i++) {
                integerList.add(arr[i][end_col]);
            }

            // printing bottom elements
            if (start_row < end_row) {
                for (int j = end_col - 1; j >= start_col; j--) {
                    integerList.add(arr[end_row][j]);
                }
            }

            // printing left elements
            if (start_col < end_col) {
                for (int i = end_row - 1; i >= start_row + 1; i--) {
                    integerList.add(arr[i][start_col]);
                }
            }

            start_col++;
            start_row++;
            end_col--;
            end_row--;
        }

        return integerList;
    }
}
