### ✔ Spiral Matrix  | C++ | Medium Level | Easy, Fast and Simple | 6ms 

<br>
This is a very simple and easy to understand solution. I traverse right and increment startRow, then traverse down and decrement endColumn, then I traverse left and decrement endRow, and finally I traverse up and increment startColumn.

The edge case here is that when I traverse left or up I have to check whether the row or column is already taken to prevent duplicates.

Any comments greatly appreciated. Please Upvote if you liked the solution :)
<br>

```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> spiralOrder(vector<vector<int>>& matrix) {
        // Take a vector to store spiral matrix.
        vector<int> v;

        // Take row and column size.
        int n = matrix.size();
        int m = matrix[0].size();

        // Take 4 variable for itteration through rows and columns.
        int startRow = 0;
        int endRow = n - 1;
        int startColumn = 0;
        int endColumn = m - 1;

        // For boundary checking in rows and columns
        while(startRow <= endRow && startColumn <= endColumn){

            // Storing starting row.
            for(int column = startColumn; column <= endColumn; column++){
                v.push_back(matrix[startRow][column]);
            }

            // Storing ending column(Leaving first elemnet which is already taken in starting row)
            for(int row = startRow + 1; row <= endRow; row++){
                v.push_back(matrix[row][endColumn]);
            }

            // Stroring ending row(Leaving last elemnet which is already taken in ending column)
            for(int column = endColumn - 1; column >= startColumn; column--){

                // Avoiding Repeating same row twice.
                if(startRow == endRow){
                    break;
                }

                v.push_back(matrix[endRow][column]);
            }

            // Storing starting column(Leaving first and last elemnet which is already taken in starting row and ending row)
            for(int row = endRow - 1; row >= startRow + 1; row--){

                // Avoiding Repeating same column twice.
                if(startColumn == endColumn){
                    break;
                }

                v.push_back(matrix[row][startColumn]);
            }

            // Increment the start row and start column. 
            // Decrement the end row and end column.
            startRow++;
            endColumn--;
            endRow--;
            startColumn++;

        }
        return v;
    }
};
```

