solutions.content:
Nice problem and I wanted to give myself the extra challenge to solve it without marking the visited cells in any way, even in place.

We can think at this problem in this way:
* we can start running through the first row, then we mark it as taken;
* then we go down the last colummn and we mark it too;
* now we do the last row (in reverse order) and we mark it;
* time to go up through the first column, up to its penultimate element (we took it when we started with the last row);
* rinse and repeat, until you have taken all the cells just once.

Now, in order to make it work without marking the explored cells in any way, we will need 4 pointers and a few more variables:
* `lmtLeft`, `lmtRight`, `lmtUp` and `lmtDown` will limit our exploration of the matrix, being initialised to the indexes of the first and last columns before we start the main loop;
* `i` is our iterator to write in `res`;
* `tot` is the overall amount of elements in the matrix, obtained by multipling `lmtRight` and `lmtDown` right before reducing them by `1` to match the indexes of the last column and row, respectively;
* `res` is our accumulator variable, already created at the right size, to avoid reallocations.

We will then create an infinite loop and:
* go right, with `x` going from `lmtLeft` to `lmtRight`, using `lmtUp` as `y`, right before increasing it, and write in `res` advancing `i`;
* check if we are done writing in `res` (`i == tot`), in which case we `break`;
* go down, with `y` going from `lmtUp` to `lmtDown`, using `lmtRight` as x`, right before decreasing it, and write in `res` advancing `i`;
* check if we are done writing in `res` (`i == tot`), in which case we `break`;
* go left, with `x` going from `lmRight` to `lmtLeft`, using `lmtDown` as `y`, right before decreasing it, and write in `res` advancing `i`;
* check if we are done writing in `res` (`i == tot`), in which case we `break`;
* go up, with `y` going from `lmtDown` to `lmtUp`, using `lmtLeft` as `x`, right before increasing it, and write in `res` advancing `i`;
* check if we are done writing in `res` (`i == tot`), in which case we `break`.

Once done, we can just `return` `res` :)

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> spiralOrder(vector<vector<int>>& arr) {
        // support variables
        int lmtLeft = 0, lmtRight = arr[0].size(), lmtUp = 0, lmtDown = arr.size(), i = 0, tot = lmtRight-- * lmtDown--;
        vector<int> res(tot);
        while (true) {
            // going right
            for (int x = lmtLeft, y = lmtUp++; x <= lmtRight; x++) res[i++] = arr[y][x];
            if (i == tot) break;
            // going down
            for (int y = lmtUp, x = lmtRight--; y <= lmtDown; y++) res[i++] = arr[y][x];
            if (i == tot) break;
            // going left
            for (int x = lmtRight, y = lmtDown--; x >= lmtLeft; x--) res[i++] = arr[y][x];
            if (i == tot) break;
            // going up
            for (int y = lmtDown, x = lmtLeft++; y >= lmtUp; y--) res[i++] = arr[y][x];
            if (i == tot) break;
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

