solutions.content:
**1. Where will the `minimum` value appear ?**
- Depending on how many times the array has been rotated 
1. If the array has been rotated *length* times (aka no rotation), the minimum is on the *leftmost*.
	- nums[left]
2. If the arry has been rotated other number of times, the minimum is at the rotation point.
	- denoted as nums[R]
- This leads us to find the rotation point. -> which is the same as [81. Search in Rotated Sorted Array II](https://leetcode.com/problems/search-in-rotated-sorted-array-ii/)

**2. What patterns we can use if an array (with duplicates) is `sorted`?**
- `nums[left] <= nums[mid] <= nums[right] `AND nums[left], nums[right], nums[mid] are not completely the same (IMPORTANT) 
- This hints us to use *boundary value comparison*. 

**3. How do we approach the solution?**
- we first want to check the three boundaries, nums[left], nums[right], nums[mid], and see if they are of the same value, 
	- if so, we can not determine which half is sorted, and have to use linear search 
	- e.g. [2, 2, 2, 2, 1, 2]

- otherwise, we check if one side is sorted
	- rotation points disturbs the patterns nums[left] <= nums[mid] <= nums[right] if it exists, but still one half of the list will remain sorted 
- `nums[left] <= nums[mid]` means left half is sorted 
	- left = mid + 1, because we know `mid` will not be the minimum as nums[left] can possibly be smaller or equal
- ` nums[mid] <= nums[right]` means right half is sorted 
	- right = mid, nums[mid] could be the minimum so it needs to be included for next check 
	- [4,5,1,2,3]

```
public int findMin(int[] nums) {
	if (nums == null || nums.length == 0) return 0; 

	int left = 0, right = nums.length - 1, mid;

	while (left < right) {
		mid = (right - left) / 2 + left; 

		// linear search if all 3 boundaries are of the SAME value
		if (nums[left] == nums[mid] && nums[mid] == nums[right]) {
			return linearSearch(nums, left, right); 
		} else if (nums[left] <= nums[mid]) {
			// left half is sorted 
			if (nums[mid] <= nums[right]) {
				// whole array is sorted 
				return nums[left]; 
			} else {
				// search right half 
				left = mid + 1; 
			}
		} else {
			// right half is sorted, search left half
			right = mid; 
		}
	}

	return nums[left]; 
}

// linear search and returns min value 
private int linearSearch(int[] nums, int left, int right) {
	int minVal = Integer.MAX_VALUE; 
	for (int i = left; i <= right; i++) {
		minVal = Math.min(nums[i], minVal);
	}
	return minVal;
}
```

