# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The given code aims to find the minimum element in a rotated sorted array by using a recursive approach.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- The code starts by calling the overloaded method findMin(nums, 0, nums.length-1) to initiate the recursive process.
- In the recursive method, several base cases are checked:
1. If right is equal to left, it means the subarray has only one element, so the minimum is the element at left.
2. If right is equal to left + 1, it means the subarray has two elements, so the minimum is the smaller of the two elements.
3. If nums[right] is greater than nums[left], it means the subarray is already sorted, and the minimum is the element at left.
4. If nums[right] is equal to nums[left], it means the subarray has repeated elements, and the minimum is searched by calling the recursive method with left incremented by 1.
5. If none of the above conditions is met, the array is rotated, and the method proceeds with finding the minimum recursively.
- The middle index is calculated as (right-left)/2 + left.
- If nums[middle] is greater than or equal to nums[left], it means the minimum lies to the right of the middle. The method calls itself with middle as the new left index.
- If nums[middle] is less than nums[left], it means the minimum lies to the left of the middle. The method calls itself with middle as the new right index.
- The method repeats steps 3-5 until the minimum element is found.
Finally, the minimum element is returned.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The time complexity of this recursive solution is O(log n) because it uses a binary search approach to find the minimum element. The array is divided in half at each step, reducing the search space.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The space complexity is O(log n) due to the recursive calls. In the worst case, the maximum number of recursive calls is proportional to the logarithm of the input size.

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int findMin(int[] nums) {
        return findMin(nums, 0, nums.length-1);
    }
    public int findMin(int[] nums, int left, int right)
    {
        if(right==left)
        {
            return nums[left];
        }
        if(right == left +1)
        {
            return Math.min(nums[left], nums[right]);
        }
        // 3 3 1 3 3 3
        int middle = (right-left)/2 + left;
        // already sorted
        if(nums[right] > nums[left])
        {
            return nums[left];
            //right shift one
        }
        else if(nums[right] == nums[left])
        {
            return findMin(nums, left+1, right);
            //go right
        }
        else if(nums[middle] >= nums[left])
        {
            return findMin(nums, middle, right);
        }
        else
        {
            return findMin(nums, left, middle);
        }
    }
}
```

