# Intuition
In a sorted array, finding a value is a simple task thanks to binary search. However, in a rotated sorted array, the task becomes a bit more challenging. Additionally, the problem statement suggests that the array could include duplicates, adding yet another layer of complexity.

# Approach
This solution takes advantage of binary search, while handling the complications introduced by the rotation and the duplicates.

The binary search strategy here is slightly modified from the traditional method to handle the rotation. The rotation splits the sorted array into two sorted segments. If the middle element is greater than the last element, the minimum value must be in the second half of the array. If the middle element is less than the last element, the minimum value must be in the first half.

Duplicates are dealt with by incrementing the start index and decrementing the end index whenever a duplicate is encountered. This way, even when the array is full of duplicates, we can efficiently reduce the search space.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
The worst-case scenario is when all elements are duplicates, and in that case, the time complexity is O(n). However, if there are no duplicates or if duplicates are evenly distributed, this approach performs far better than a linear scan.

- Space complexity:
The space complexity is O(1) since only 3 integers are initalised to hold the positions

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public static int findMin(int[] nums) {
        int high = nums.length - 1;
        int low = 0;
        int mid = high / 2;
        while (low < high) {
            if (nums[mid] > nums[high]) {
                low = mid + 1;
                mid = low + (high - low) / 2;
            } else if (nums[mid] < nums[high]) {
                high = mid;
                mid = low + (high - low) / 2;
            } else {
                // Drop duplicates and try again
                if (nums[mid] == nums[high])
                    high--;
                if (nums[mid] == nums[low])
                    low++;
                mid = low + (high - low) / 2;
            }
        }
        return nums[mid];
    }
}
```

