# Intuition
This problem is an extension of binary search in which the intuition is to find the pivot of the array where the rotation is taking place.

# Approach
Step1: Run a while loop from starting index to ending index
Step2: Check if the array is sorted. If sorted return the starting index
Step3: Find the mid of the starting and ending index. Check if the mid element is smaller than the starting index. If true then increase the starting index with index of mid element + 1
Step4: Check if the mid element is smaller than the ending index. If true then decrease the ending element to mid index -1;
Step5: If the starting index value and mid index value is same then increment the starting index by 1 else decrement the ending index by 1.
Step6: Check the min value at each iteration and store it. Then check it with the mid element value at each iteration. At last return the min value.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(N)

- Space complexity:
O(1)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int findMin(vector<int>& nums) {
        int l = 0, r = nums.size()-1;
        int res = nums[0];

        while(l <= r){
            if(nums[l] < nums[r]){
                res = min(res, nums[l]);
                break;
            }

            int mid = (l + r) >> 1;
            cout << mid << " ";
            res = min(res, nums[mid]);
            if(nums[mid] > nums[l]){
                l = mid + 1;
            }
            else if(nums[mid] < nums[r]){
                r = mid-1;
            }
            else{
                if(nums[l] == nums[mid]){
                    l++;
                }else{
                    r--;
                }
            }
        }

        return res;
    }
};
```

