**Dynamic Programming:**
```
public int maxEnvelopes(int[][] envelopes) {
        int max=1,n=envelopes.length;
        if(n<=1) return n;
        Arrays.sort(envelopes,(a,b)->{
            if(a[0]==b[0]) return b[1]-a[1];
            else return a[0]-b[0];
        });
        int[] dp=new int[n];
        Arrays.fill(dp,1);
        for(int i=1;i<n;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<i;j++){
                if(envelopes[j][0]<envelopes[i][0] && envelopes[j][1]<envelopes[i][1] 
                  &&
                    dp[j]+1>dp[i]
                  )
                    dp[i]=1+dp[j];
            }
            max=Math.max(max,dp[i]);
        }
        return max;
```
**Binary Search :**
```
class Solution {
    public int maxEnvelopes(int[][] envelopes) {
        int n=envelopes.length,len=1;
        if(n<=1) return n;
        Arrays.sort(envelopes,(a,b)->{
            if(a[0]==b[0]) return b[1]-a[1];
            else return a[0]-b[0];
        });
         int[][] sorted=new int[n][2];sorted[0]=envelopes[0];
        for(int[] arr : envelopes){
            int  index=insertion_position(sorted,arr,0,len-1);
            sorted[index]=arr;
            if(len==index ) len++;    
        }
       return len;
    }
    private int insertion_position(int[][] input,int[] arr,int st,int end){
       if(input[end][0]<arr[0] && input[end][1]<arr[1]) return end+1;
        while(st<=end){
            int mid=st+(end-st)/2;
            if(input[mid][1]>arr[1]) end=mid-1;
            else if(input[mid][1]<arr[1])  st=mid+1;
            else return mid;
        }
        return st;
    }
}
```
***Here we sort array as ascending order of width, and if width is same then sort in descending order of height.***
Lets assume that there are many envelops with same height, then it is better to choose bigger envelop first as it has better chance to fit the LIS.
**Ex:** [1,1] [2,2] [3,3] [4,3] [4,4].
Here if sort in ascending order of width and height, then it would result in LIS od [1,1] [2,2] [4,3]. But if we sort in descending order of height if width is same then, it would result in [1,1] [2,2] [3,3] [4,4].
Ex: [1,1] [2,2] [3,3] [4,5] [4,4] [5,5]
[4,5] has larger area than [3,3] so insert [4,5] at end.
[4,4] is not larger than [4,5]. So insert [4,4] at its ceil position i.e., at [4,5] beacuse it has better chance in future to form a LIS.

By sorting in descending order if width are same, what we are essentially doing is by wrapping smaller envelopes with largest evelope then trying to check if it is possible to get LIS of same length with evelops with same width and samller heights, so that in future we get bigger LIS .

