        /*
        Approach: Brute force approach will be for every possible combination of A, B, C and D, check if that leads to 0 sum.
                  But this will have e time complexity of O(n^4), which is not that good.
                  In this approach, we first calculate the sum of each A and B, and the count of the sum in a HashMap.
                  So, now we have each (A+B) and their frequencies.
                  Now we need to find which possible C and D combos along with A+B combos sum to 0.
                  For that, we loop through C and D, and check if we have the complement sums in our A+B combo HashMap.
                  If we have, that means for each count of that A+B combo, we our this C+D combo can lead to 0 sum.
                  So we add the frequency of that A+B combo to our sumCount.

        Complexity analysis: Time: O(n^2)
                             Space: O(n^2)
        */

        HashMap<Integer, Integer> sumABFrequencyMap = new HashMap<>();

        for(int a : A){
            for(int b : B){
                sumABFrequencyMap.put(a+b, sumABFrequencyMap.getOrDefault(a+b,0)+1);
            }
        }

