The intuition behind the solution is simple.
Let us take look to the intuition:-
1/ In simple addition we have two things like in a+b we have two side (first one is a) and the (second one is b)
	keeping this in our mind we can proceed with this problem.
2/ Here also we will have two sides (As we know we 4 nums so we will divide them into 2-2 group) i.e nums1 and nums2 will be on one side and nums3 and nums4 will  be on another side.
*                               **** nums1 + nums2  =  -(nums3+num4) ****


Here is my solution to the problem:-
```
class Solution {
public:
    int fourSumCount(vector<int>& nums1, vector<int>& nums2, vector<int>& nums3, vector<int>& nums4) {
        unordered_map<int,int>mp;
        int cnt =0;
        for(int i=0;i<nums1.size();i++){
            for(int j=0;j<nums2.size();j++){
                int sum = nums1[i] + nums2[j];
                mp[sum]++;
            }
        }
        for(int i=0;i<nums3.size();i++){
            for(int j=0;j<nums4.size();j++){
                int sum = (-1)*(nums3[i] + nums4[j]);
                if(mp[sum]){
                    cnt+= mp[sum];
                }
            }
        }
        return cnt;
    }
};
```

