**Idea:**
* Think in reverse, find maximum number of bricks which are starting from the same position along the x-axis. If we subtract this number from `numRows`, we get our answer.
* In order to maintain the maximum number of bricks which are starting from a position along the x-axis, we need to maintain a hashmap of position vs count.
* Also, ignore the last brick, because we can't have the start/end vertical line as our answer.

```
public int leastBricks(List<List<Integer>> wall) {
	if (wall.isEmpty()) {
		return 0;
	}

	Map<Integer, Integer> openingMap = new HashMap<>();
	int maxOpening = 0;

	for (List<Integer> row : wall) {
		int pos = 0;
		for (int i = 0; i < row.size()-1; i++) {
			int b = row.get(i);
			pos += b;
			openingMap.put(pos, openingMap.getOrDefault(pos, 0) + 1);
			maxOpening = Math.max(maxOpening, openingMap.get(pos));
		}
	}

	return wall.size() - maxOpening;
}
```

