// The point here to consider is the most EDGES the line crosses the less bricks the line goes through.
// For all the rows of bricks, find each edge index and store in a map with its freq. 
// Do it for every row and store all the edges in each row and if you find an edge index already in map, UPDATE the count
// The MAX COUNT for some edge index will help in drawing the line

// Thanks @kunalchand234 for amazing explanation. The pictures are utilized from his post.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/597fa89f-1895-46a7-965c-4f4424424dfb_1640854273.8434193.png)

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/f091b4dc-2d36-4c69-9250-1c0f848924d1_1640854289.3657134.png)

The blue box in below pictures which bricks the line crosses
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/cb2710ea-5f0b-4839-9e2c-c1bc3cfa97b8_1640854354.414998.png)


// See here for detailed solution : https://leetcode.com/problems/brick-wall/discuss/888577/IntuitionC%2B%2BWith-PicturesHashMapDetailed-ExplanationCommentsSolutionCode

// TC : O(M * N) -> M = walls.length, N = avg num of bricks in each row
// SC : O(N) -> N = avg num of bricks in each row

```
class Solution {
    public int leastBricks(List<List<Integer>> wall) {
        Map<Integer, Integer> edgeMap = new HashMap<>(); // key -> edge, value -> freq of edge

        int count = 0; // max count for edge index

        for(List<Integer> bricks : wall) {
            int edge = 0;
            for(int i = 0; i < bricks.size() - 1; i++) { // -1 because we do not want to use last edge
                edge += bricks.get(i); // every time adding brick size will gice next edge
                edgeMap.put(edge, edgeMap.getOrDefault(edge, 0) + 1);
                count = Math.max(count, edgeMap.get(edge));
            }
        }

        return wall.size() - count;
    }
}
```

