solutions.content:
This problem might tempt you to go for some complex logic in which you compute intervals one step at a time, but in the end all you need to get is the position and thus the frequency of all the gaps in the wall, then return the total number of layers in the wall minus the minimum amount of them.

To do so, we will first of all define a few support variables:
* `len` will store the length of the wall (in levels);
* `res` is were we will store our best result - initially set to be equal to `len` (edge/worst case: no gaps);
* `c` is going to store the cumulative total of all the elements of each layer (save for the last);
* `um` is where we will store the frequency of each gap.

We will then iterate through each `level` of `wall` and:
* set `c` to be `0`;
* loop through all the elements of `level` but the last one (which is never needed) and:
	* increase the cumulative length of the current `level` with `c += level[i]`;
	* increase the frequency of that length in `um`.

Next, we will just iterate through all the frequencies we found (with `e.second`) and update `res` to be the minimum between its current value and `len - e.second` (i.e.: the amount of gaps not present for that layer).

Once done, we can return `res` :)

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int leastBricks(vector<vector<int>>& wall) {
        // support variables
        int len = wall.size(), res = len, c;
        unordered_map<int, int> um;
        // getting the frequencies of each gap
        for (auto &level: wall) {
            c = 0;
            for (int i = 0, lmt = level.size() - 1; i < lmt; i++) um[c += level[i]]++;
        }
        // getting the most frequent gap
        for (auto e: um) {
            res = min(res, len - e.second);
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

Micro-optimised alternative in which we just subtract from `len` in the end, instead of doing so every time we update `res`:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int leastBricks(vector<vector<int>>& wall) {
        // support variables
        int len = wall.size(), res = 0, c;
        unordered_map<int, int> um;
        // getting the frequencies of each gap
        for (auto &level: wall) {
            c = 0;
            for (int i = 0, lmt = level.size() - 1; i < lmt; i++) um[c += level[i]]++;
        }
        // getting the most frequent gap
        for (auto e: um) {
            res = max(res, e.second);
        }
        return len - res;
    }
};
```

