A lot of people have posted solution to this problem using Map. But to be honest, I treated this problem as an aptitude problem rather than a coding question.
I felt like , "Okay!! , how would I solve this problem in real life if I encountered this situation" and Bingo!!!! I solved it in a way that involves none of the fancy coding knowledge.

Okay, Lets see the intuition behind solving this problem:
1. So, in every row, after placing the first brick of the repective sizes in each row, HOW to ascertain the least number of bricks crossing vertical line??

2. Here an important observation is that the  **the number of the minimum length of combined bricks in each row** gives us the maximum number of bricks through which a line can be drawn without crossing. This gives is the minimum number of bricks through which a line can be drawn crossing them. **This is the determinant of the problem.** 

3. This is true only if we first try to fill the rows which have the minimum length after placing bricks in each row.

4. But why **Minimum** ???? Because with each row having bricks till a minimum length, the minimum number of bricks through which a line can be drawn can be determined. Lets take an example:
Consider a brick length of 1 unit as #.
1st row :  ################################
2nd row:  #################
3rd row:  #################
4th row:  #######################################
5th row:  #################

Here 2nd, 3rd and 5th are minimum. So, the Number of the minimum length of combined bricks in each row=3.
So the minimum number of bricks crossing the line would be= 
Number of rows-Number of the minimum length of combined bricks in each row=5-3=2

**Here we took the help of minimum length because if we consider other lengths, then we are never sure whether the row having bricks of length shorter than that will cross the vertical line or not if a line was drawn from larger length edge.**
And BINGO!!! It hits you!!!

3. Now, the thing that makes us think that the solution is DIFFICULT is that if a Map is not used and the above intuition is used, then how to traverse the given list???

4. To answer this Qs, Read point number 3 carefully.

5. We keep track of the length of bricks in each row in an Array **value[]** and the last index whose size that has been taken into value array in array **index[]**

Java Code:
```
public int leastBricks(List<List<Integer>> wall) {

        //min is the required answer...
        int min=Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        int row=wall.size();
        int col=0;
        for(int i=0;i<wall.get(0).size();i++){
            col=col+wall.get(0).get(i);
        }

		//Contains the last index of each row that has been added to value
        int index[]=new int[row];

		//Contains the length of bricks in each row
        int value[]=new int[row];

		//minimum brick length in each row
        int minimumTillNow=Integer.MAX_VALUE;

		//count the number of minimum brick length in each row
        int count=0;

		//Adding first brick in each row
        for(int i=0;i<row;i++){
            int x=wall.get(i).get(0);
            value[i]=x;
            if(minimumTillNow>x){
                count=1;
                minimumTillNow=x;
            }
            else if(minimumTillNow==x){
                count++;
            }
        }

		//Base case [[1], [1], [1]]
		//In this case, the line will cross bricks=number of rows=row
        if(minimumTillNow==col){
            return row;
        }
        min=Math.min(min,row-count);

		//Loop until all the bricks are added to the arangement
        while(true){
            count=0;
            int tempMin=Integer.MAX_VALUE;

			//In this loop, we use the Point 3 i.e
		   //we try to fill up rows with minimum length bricks first
            for(int i=0;i<row;i++){
                if(value[i]==minimumTillNow&&index[i]<(wall.get(i).size()-1)){
                    value[i]=value[i]+wall.get(i).get(index[i]+1);
                    index[i]++;
                }
                if(tempMin>value[i]){
                count=1;
                tempMin=value[i];
                }
                else if(tempMin==value[i]){
                    count++;
                }

            }
            minimumTillNow=tempMin;

			//All bricks have been added to the arrangement
			//So, minimumTillNow will become equal to the number of columns
			//So, this is the right boundary case, Break the loop here.
            if(minimumTillNow==col){
                break;
            }

			//This is obvious
            min=Math.min(min,row-count);
        }
        return min;
    }
```
