/*
PEDAC Process

Understand the Problem (P):

We have a rectangular wall composed of rows of bricks.
We want to draw a vertical line from the top to the bottom and cross the least number of bricks.
The width of the wall is the length of the longest row.
We are given a list of lists wall where each sublist represents a row of bricks.
We need to find the minimum number of crossed bricks after drawing the vertical line.
Examples/Test Cases (E):

Let's consider some examples to understand the problem better:

wall = [[1,2,2,1], [3,1,2], [1,3,2], [2,4], [3,1,2], [1,3,1,1]]
Drawing the vertical line at the 4th index (1-indexed) avoids crossing any bricks, so the result is 0.
wall = [[1], [1], [1]]
In this case, there is only one column, so the line will cross all the bricks. The result is 3.
Data Structure (D):

To solve this problem, we may use a dictionary (or map) to keep track of the number of times we encounter a specific position while iterating through the rows.

Algorithm (A):

Initialize a dictionary to store the frequency of positions where the vertical line crosses.
Iterate through each row in the wall.
For each row, calculate the cumulative sum of brick widths from left to right.
For each cumulative sum (position), update the dictionary to record how many times we've encountered that position.
Find the position with the highest frequency in the dictionary.
Return the total number of rows minus the highest frequency (minimum number of crossed bricks).
*/

/**
 * @param {number[][]} wall
 * @return {number}
 */
var leastBricks = function(wall) {
    let countGaps = { 0: 0};

    for (let i = 0; i < wall.length; i += 1) {
        let sum = 0;
        for (let j = 0; j < wall[i].length - 1; j += 1) {
            sum += wall[i][j];
            if (String(sum) in countGaps) {
                let value = countGaps[String(sum)];
                value += 1;
                countGaps[String(sum)] = value;
            } else {
                countGaps[String(sum)] = 1;
            }
        }
    }

    console.log(countGaps);

    let gaps = Object.values(countGaps);
    let maxGap = Math.max(...gaps);
    console.log(`maximum gap is ${maxGap}.`);
    return wall.length - maxGap;
};

// time coplexity O(n^2) or the number of bricks we have in our input.
// space complexity: whatever the length of the rows happend to be.
```

